[Auction "E"]
1H 1S 2H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "4076cc2555c61677d39af35586058c62f11b5cc8bbbb53c1d1bb52086c8f09bf"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/defensive_signals"]
[Student "W"]
{You are South. The bidding has been as shown. You led the \SA, North plays the \S9, East the \S5. You assume North has signaled you to continue \Ss, so you play the \SQ. On this trick North plays the \S3 and East the \S8. How will you continue? 

You know that both North and East are now void of \Ss. You might just switch suits, but you have a better choice.

If you play your \SQ, North won't bother ruffing, East <b>WILL</b> ruff and dummy's \SJ will be established as a winner.

The best procedure is to lead a low \S. North will ruff and East will over-ruff but by playing this way you stop the establishment of West's \SJ. As you can see, East would have been able to discard a loser on that \SJ if you hadn't played this way.}
[Play "W"]SA

